{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613536"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:36:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:36:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16313"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16313"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.72,0.04,0,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9004"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70413"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9004"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16313"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55877"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1694"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"6873"},{"type":"tags","id":"8094"},{"type":"tags","id":"9626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21429"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21434"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70413"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGroup A Streptococcus can cause bacterial tonsillitis, which may lead to both local suppurative and systemic non-suppurative complications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a non-suppurative complication of streptococcal tonsillitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Peritonsillar abscess","Rheumatic fever","Retropharyngeal abscess","Parapharyngeal abscess","Cervical lymphadenitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eperitonsillar abscess\u003C/strong\u003E (quinsy) is a suppurative complication caused by direct spread of bacteria into the peritonsillar space. Similarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Eretropharyngeal abscess\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eparapharyngeal abscess\u003C/strong\u003E are local suppurative complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatic fever\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-suppurative complication that occurs due to an autoimmune response triggered by molecular mimicry between streptococcal M protein and human cardiac tissue. This can lead to carditis, arthritis, chorea, and other systemic manifestations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical lymphadenitis\u003C/strong\u003E is another suppurative complication involving infection of local lymph nodes. Other important non-suppurative complications include post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis and scarlet fever.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Group A Streptococcus infection can trigger autoimmune responses leading to rheumatic fever through molecular mimicry.","Non-suppurative complications of streptococcal tonsillitis include rheumatic fever, post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis, and scarlet fever.","Suppurative complications like peritonsillar abscess (quinsy) are caused by direct bacterial spread."],"references":["Stolleman, Rheumatic fever, https://www.thelancet.com/article/S0140-6736(96)06364-7/abstract, 1997"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55877"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16313"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevi